{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17414727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17414727"},"attributes":{"position":41,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T08:57:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T08:57:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19550"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568175"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:10:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:10:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19550"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"19550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19550"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.02,0.11,0.15,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12320"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107507"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12320"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19550"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89987"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4957"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11517"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29334"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29664"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40061"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107507"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with three days of diarrhoea and vomiting. She has a previous STEMI and reflux, and she takes esomeprazole, atorvastatin, aspirin, perindopril and metoprolol. She is able to drink fluids and her last vomiting or diarrhoea episode was six hours ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe appears tired but alert. Her pulse rate is 101/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. She has dry mucous membranes and generalised abdominal tenderness. The capillary refill time is 3 seconds.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral rehydration solution","Intramuscular ondansetron","Transfer to Emergency Department","Intravenous Hartmann\u0027s solution","Clear fluids only"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs of moderate dehydration in the primary care setting. The key clinical findings include borderline tachycardia, dry mucous membranes, and delayed capillary refill. Importantly, her last episode of vomiting or diarrhoea was six hours ago, suggesting that the acute phase may be settling. She remains alert, able to take oral fluids and is not in hypovolemic shock, making oral rehydration a viable option. Her blood glucose level would also be taken at this time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral rehydration solution\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management. Given that she has not vomited or had diarrhoea for six hours and can tolerate oral fluids, a trial of oral rehydration is warranted. It is safe, effective, and can be easily administered in the community setting. WHO-standard oral rehydration solution contains appropriate concentrations of glucose and electrolytes to optimise fluid absorption. If oral rehydration fails (persistent vomiting or inability to tolerate fluids), then anti-emetics and/or intravenous fluids with Emergency Department transfer would be considered. Ideally, she would be observed for a short period of time after ORS consumption to review the response, and have a follow-up within 24 hours given her co-morbidities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular ondansetron\u003C/strong\u003E may help with nausea but does not address the primary problem of dehydration. Additionally, since she has not vomited for six hours, anti-emetics are not the immediate priority. Oral anti-emetics would be preferred if needed or able to tolerate oral medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer to Emergency Department\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary for moderate dehydration that can be managed with oral rehydration in the community, especially when the patient has been symptom-free for six hours. Hospital resources should be reserved for more severe cases or those failing oral rehydration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous Hartmann\u0027s solution\u003C/strong\u003E, while an appropriate fluid choice for dehydration, is not necessary as first-line treatment when oral rehydration is possible and the patient has been stable for six hours. This would require hospital admission or referral to an emergency department. The choice of intravenous solution is based on the patient\u0027s requirement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClear fluids only\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate for treating dehydration as it does not provide the necessary electrolytes and can potentially worsen electrolyte imbalances. Plain water or other clear fluids lack the optimal glucose-to-sodium ratio that facilitates fluid absorption in the small intestine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Oral rehydration solution is the first-line treatment for mild to moderate dehydration in primary care.","Assessment of mental status, vital signs, and capillary refill are key components in evaluating dehydration severity.","Intravenous fluids should be reserved for severe dehydration or those unable to tolerate oral intake."],"references":["Medecin Sans Frontiers Clinical guideline - Diagnosis and Treatment Manual. Dehydration. Medecin Sans Fronters. 2025. Available at: https://medicalguidelines.msf.org/en/viewport/CG/english/dehydration-62194197.html","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital, Melbourne, Australia, Clinical Practice Guideline on Dehydration, [Internet, last updated 2020].  Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/dehydration/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89987"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19550"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89987"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-30T19:51:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-30T19:52:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12320"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107507"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/73"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Post-graduate","synonyms":null,"description":"Not suitable for a medical student","position":2,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"